    {
      "id": "369df61dd1fdf0463f6a509bb759efb524f5e1fa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 02:08:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThe D_HA Flag is enabled by default in production, and this isn't really related to recovery in any case.\n\nIt would be better to log this using an appropriate mask like D_CACHE and then enable this flag in the tests that you are trying to debug instead of adding overhead for all production users of Lustre.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8d3c864fc17994fce0d4762ee7837c1292dde08c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-11-06 02:22:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> The D_HA Flag is enabled by default in production, and this isn't really related to recovery in any case.\n> It would be better to log this using an appropriate mask like D_CACHE and then enable this flag in the tests that you are trying to debug instead of adding overhead for all production users of Lustre.\n\nWe have used \"D_HA\" for osd_sync(), it is found in the LFSCK test log. On the other hand, dt_sync() is not often triggered, even though the log for dt_sync() uses \"D_HA\", it should not cause a lot of debug message.\n\nIf we replace the \"D_HA\" with \"D_CACHE\" here and enable \"D_CACHE\" in test, then the potential trouble will be:\n1) The log size in test, because we have more other use cases for \"D_CACHE\" in Lustre.\n2) The performance in VM environment, we have met similar trouble before.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
